Yes, items can populate your planning board automatically without any manual 
input by using the built-in Auto-add to project workflow. 

Instead of opening your project and manually clicking to add tasks, GitHub 
continuously scans designated repositories and injects them onto the board 
based on rules you define. 

⚡ How it Works (No Manual Input)
You create a funnel using filters. The second a developer creates an issue
or pull request that matches that specific funnel, it instantly lands on
your planning board. 

Popular Automated Triggers
By Label: Automatically add everything tagged as bug or epic.
By Status: Automatically add all newly opened pull requests so the team 
can see incoming code reviews.
By Assignee: Automatically add any issue that gets assigned to a specific person. 

🛠️ How to Set Up Auto-Add Workflows
You can configure your project's automated inflows in a few clicks: 

Open your project on GitHub and click the three dots (...) in the top right.
Click on ⚙️ Workflows.
Under the Default workflows list, click on Auto-add to project.
Click Edit in the top right corner.
Select the repository you want to pull issues/PRs from.
Set your filter criteria (e.g., typing is:issue label:sprint-1 or simply 
leaving it open to pull all new issues).
Click Save and turn on workflow. 

💡 Pro-Tip: You can duplicate this specific workflow multiple times if you 
need to pull in automated items from several different repositories at once! 

